- Wed 3 Jun 2020 17:01 CET. WHO reports new cases
[Reuters, abridged, edited]
https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-congo/two-more-people-infected-with-ebola-in-new-congo-outbreak-who-says-idUSKBN23A39C
[Byline: Emma Farge and Hereward Holland]

Two more people infected with Ebola in new Congo outbreak, WHO says. An epidemic of the virus on the other side of the country has killed more than 2200 people since 2018.

The 2 outbreaks are the same strain of the virus, which means the same vaccines can be used to help contain its spread, health officials say, although they are not thought to be linked.

"The latest person confirmed with Ebola attended the burial of one of the 1st cases, but was detected in the town of Bikoro, 150 kilometres (about 93 mi) away from Mbandaka," WHO Director-General Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus told journalists. "This means that 2 health zones are now affected."

Mbandaka suffered a small Ebola outbreak in 2018 in which 33 people died. The use of a vaccine and swift containment efforts including mobile handwashing stations and a door-to-door education campaign kept it at bay.

On Wednesday [3 Jun 2020] almost 50 health workers from WHO and its partners arrived in Mbandaka with 3600 doses of Ebola vaccine and 2000 cartridges for lab testing, Tedros said.

